Subject: CI Build Failure – AdProvider & System.Web.Services DLL Dependency in WCI_APIs

Hi [Architect Name],

Hope you are doing well.

I wanted to bring to your attention a CI build issue we are currently facing in the WCI project and seek your guidance on the best approach to resolve it.

**Current Situation:**
The AuthenticationController.cs in WCI_APIs is actively using two legacy assemblies:
• AdProvider.dll – used for [Active Directory / user authentication logic]
• System.Web.Services.dll – used for [SOAP / web service calls]

What I Already Tried:
I stored the DLLs in /WCI_APIs/libs folder and added it to .gitignore to keep them out of source control. This works locally since the DLLs are physically present on developer machines. However, the CI agent clones only what is in the repository — so the libs folder never reaches the build agent, causing the failure. This means we cannot use gitignore as a solution here — the DLLs either need to be in the repo, in a NuGet feed, or the code needs to be rewritten.

These DLLs are currently stored in the /WCI_APIs/libs folder locally, and the build works fine on local machines. However, since the CI agent runs on Linux with .NET 8, the build is failing with the following errors:

• CS0246: 'AdProvider' could not be found
• CS0234: 'Services' does not exist in namespace 'System.Web'

**The Core Problem:**
System.Web.Services is a .NET Framework (Windows-only) assembly and is not supported on .NET 8 / Linux environments. AdProvider.dll is also not available on the CI agent.

**I understand your preference is to avoid including these DLLs directly in the repository.** Given this constraint, I would like your guidance on which approach you would prefer us to take:

Option 1 – Rewrite using .NET 8 compatible libraries:
• Replace AdProvider with Microsoft.Identity.Client (MSAL) or System.DirectoryServices.AccountManagement
• Replace System.Web.Services with HttpClient or System.ServiceModel

Option 2 – Host DLLs as an internal NuGet package in Azure Artifacts:
• Package AdProvider as an internal NuGet feed so it is consumed cleanly without storing raw DLLs in source control

Option 3 – Temporarily include libs folder in the repository:
• As a short-term fix to unblock the CI pipeline while the permanent solution is implemented

I am ready to proceed with whichever approach you recommend. Please let me know your preferred direction so I can plan the implementation accordingly.

Thank you for your time and guidance.

